Inflation rises in Europe due to food
Accelerating inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the constant rise in food prices.
November price growth in 13 eurozone countries was higher than expected, with annual inflation of 3.1 percent after 2.6 percent in October, the Luxembourg Statistical Office of the Union said.
The official forecast was only 3%, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian emission banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the basic interest rate, with the reduction, along with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, leading to an inflation spiral.
The ECB would like to keep inflation rates below 2%, but close to them.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it must "dissuade" inflation so that it does not have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, inflation of 3.3 percent in November was a 15-year record; in Spain, it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has spilled upwards due to sharply rising food and energy prices.
Wheat prices rose by 88 percent, and soybeans reached their highest value since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil in the world markets this year rose by 52 percent and last month already cost one barrel of black gold almost $ 100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 percent in 2008 to 2.5 percent this year, but it will fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
According to analysts, the level of 12-month inflation in the next 3-4 months will remain at about 3 percent, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice over the course of 2008.
