The most expensive is Auchan, almost a fifth more expensive than Tesco
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs trade triangle maintained an average of 16% increase in the price level last year, with the difference that there was no increase in VAT this year.
Newspaper Napi Gazdaság
The usual Napi Gazdaság Christmas shopping basket in the Budaörs trade triangle grew by an average of 16 percent this year, but in all hypermarkets, the price showed an increase of more than a thousand forints.
Since prices in food supermarkets "soared" in December last year, there was not such a drastic increase in percentage due to the previous high base.
However, it is certainly disappointing for consumers that what they could have bought last year at a price of less than nine thousand forints, they will not buy now even for ten thousand.
The daily consumption basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand forints by at least 91 forints.
The highest price of the basket was 10 573 forints.
(In 2003, the consumption basket cost 6,800 forints.)
The price of Unico and live fish remained almost at last year’s level, but very expensive cruel breasts, nuts and also poppy.
The prices of bread and flour were consistent with the data of the Central Statistical Office, although in Auchan we found a kilogram of bread even for 139 forints.
The competition did not go with the price of the product below 200 forints.
Similarly, it was surprising in this store that the price of a two-liter Coca Cola in a returnable bottle was below 200 forints, so even with a deposit, the product cost only 257 forints.
This year, however, the Napi Gazdaság Auchan appeared to be the most expensive, while the Cora appeared to be the cheapest.
According to our calculations, the prices in the Napi Gazdaság consumer basket rose by 15 percent compared to last year’s prices at Christmas, while Tesco and Auchan raised by about 18 percent.
When comparing last year’s highest and this year’s lowest consumption basket values, the difference was 12 percent, while the increase between last year’s lowest and this year’s highest was 21 percent.
On average, the increase in forints was 1,480.
The average price increase last year was 1,206 forints, with prices affected by VAT growth last Christmas.
It was this process that disrupted trade, and it was evident that the department stores could not decide how large a price range they were to set for each product, as they could not predict the effect that the change in prices would have on consumption.
(If the trader misplans the speed of circulation of a given product, a significant profit may be lost due to the price range adjusted to the intensity of circulation.)
Due to VAT last year, the rise in the price of the Napi Gazdaság consumer basket was so extreme that the price of the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than in 2006, while the price difference for the cheapest one was 844 forints.
This year, the most expensive basket now cost 1,630 forints more than last year and also the cheapest one rose by 1,284 forints.
When comparing the two Christmas seasons, the price increases were catastrophic, with daily commodities in hypermarkets rising by more than 30 percent in less than 20 months.
(This, among other things, is not entirely confirmed by the Central Statistical Office’s data: it has measured a price increase of more than 30 per cent over 12 months for several basic foods.
In addition to flour, for example, in the case of eggs.)
