However, as we know, in rural areas, turnover is lower, with multiple international chains complaining to research firms that sales are lagging behind their plans, not only in the case of food, but also in the case of durable consumer goods.
Saving on disinfectants in many places
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection were registered in hospitals, mainly due to inappropriate use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, overcrowding of beds, overload of staff stopping diseases do not help, says the Primary of the National Epidemiological Center.
In many places, they also save on disinfectants.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of St. John’s Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were found in a man who was admitted to hospital after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred in the same place at the beginning of the year.
A patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but shortly afterwards he had to return with an MRSA infection and because of the bacteria in his body, one important operation could not be performed.
As of December 10, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been reported to the National Nesocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröczová, head of the National Epidemiological Center.
This means that so many infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have been safely registered in hospitals, others are unknown.
Nearly two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant golden staphylococcus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) is carried by a third of people in the nose without causing disease.
SA infections (e.g. cervical inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, morning infections) respond well to antibiotics and can be well treated.
However, when antibiotics are administered excessively or inappropriately, a bacteria that responds well to antibiotics develops into a bacteria that is highly resistant to antibiotics and that spreads rapidly in unsuitable hospital conditions.
Especially in the case of temporary or permanent poor functioning of the immune system in patients with a weakened body, low body weight or in patients in old age, it can cause serious hospital infections, for example, morning infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the chief physician of St. John’s Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, such infections belong to daily practice in hospitals.
"The infection must not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is not just there," said Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of the disease agent is not investigated."
Resistant to antibiotics
"We are isolating these patients, treating them with rubber gloves and masks, and we have the necessary antibiotics to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first examined to see if MRSA is present in their body, but infection can not always be avoided.
Sampling is out of fashion
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and conditions in home hospitals are not favorable for the prevention of the emergence and spread of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröczová.
Since this infection is common in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should check patients and isolate MRSA carriers immediately.
However, microbiological sampling in Hungarian hospitals is not in vogue.
The National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases are detected if the patient is suffering from a noticeable MRSA infection, said the head of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate treatment of antibiotics in the field of human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, diseases.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, or microbiological tests should be carried out, in order to prevent the development of drug resistance, but even hospitals do not comply with this in all cases.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in primary and outpatient care, Karolina Böröczová said.
Saves on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA is most often spread among patients through medical personnel.
Therefore, hand washing and the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are serious shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection and touch, but in home hospitals it is not always possible to isolate infected patients.
On the contrary, the rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
As Karolina Böröczová noted, unfortunately, we can also see that in hospitals that are in an unfavourable material situation, there is a saving on disinfectants, there are few nurses and a lot of patients, which increases the chances of infection.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where the necessary protective measures are observed, such infections are shown to be less or the further spread of the disease agent can be stopped.
Government Program against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is combated everywhere.
For example, in England, the government has written a program to prevent or reduce MRSA.
As the programme appears to be successful, according to published data, MRSA infections in England are showing a declining trend.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) prioritises the prevention of MRSA and hospital infections caused by MRSA.
The police captain who caused the fatal accident was not drunk.
