Bulgaria is a real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is overwhelming - the attention of the whole of Europe is turning to the formerly somewhat neglected Balkan country.
What, where and who is buying on the EU’s currently cheapest but rapidly rising market?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The most sought-after East European destination for property purchases is now undoubtedly Bulgaria with its cheap ski apartments and houses on the sea coast.
Of the mountains, the most popular are the areas of Bansko, Borovets, Pamprovo and Vitosha, on the sea coast Albena, Golden Sands, Sunny Beach, the ancient cities of Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are also looking for real estate in the vicinity of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to analysts from Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later the central part of the country - for example, Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will arouse the interest of investors, and more and more people are shopping in the vicinity of the extremely cheap city of Ruse.
Also, the capital of Sofia is a promise of enticing opportunities, business and office space promise the highest return.
Bulgaria is on its way to becoming one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe, becoming a sought-after destination in addition to the summer and winter seasons in the next two seasons.
Predictive investors are already buying in large quantities, for example in the Bansko area.
According to analysts, property buyers in Bulgaria are also trying to change their lives and lifestyles.
Most of the customers come from England, but there are also buyers from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly also from Romania.
There are also Maltese and Cypriot investors, and there are traditionally many Russian customers in the Black Sea and in the ski paradises.
Foreign buyers can be divided into three groups, says Georgiy Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Settling people buy either renovated properties worth 50-100 thousand euros, or decayed old houses for 5-15 thousand euros, which they then renovate.
They require good accessibility and communication possibilities, the proximity of a large city, shops and, as a rule, a local doctor is important for them.
The second category is chat buyers (Bulgaria ranked among the top 10 German holiday destinations in December).
The third group consists of commercial investors, who buy in the hope of an increase in value in the medium or long term.
The price increase in real estate in the capital is continuous, as demand is growing stronger.
Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices in the European Union, but has grown by 21% annually over the past five years.
The increase in property prices far outweighs the increase in wages.
Fodor and Hungarian 6%
According to the Minister of Environment and Water, Gábor Fodor, meetings of experts will be closed on Tuesday, and after the official opening on Wednesday, the international conference on the climate regime after 2012 will continue with ministerial talks.
Experts and policymakers from 192 countries are negotiating the Bali Roadmap, which addresses efforts following the emission reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol in force until 2012.
At the moment, there is a heated debate about them between developing and developed countries.
The United States has also announced that it does not want to negotiate exact figures now, although it is in favour of an agreement to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
Another big question for the conference is whether the developed countries will agree, in addition to reducing emissions, to provide both material and technological assistance to the countries that rely on it.
The agreement was also born on subsidies for developing countries.
The subsidy fund, established by the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member Steering Board, most likely within the framework of the UN World Environment Programme (GEF) - we can read in the journal Piac és Profit.
Hungarian 6%
On behalf of Hungary, Environment and Water Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leadership in global climate protection efforts and to help create a new international agreement by 2009.
The minister said the EU is committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent from 1990 levels by 2020, regardless of the success of the post-2012 agreement, and is ready to commit to up to 30 percent reductions if other developed regions of the world, or developed countries, are willing to accept responsibilities and commitments appropriate to their capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 set themselves the goal of a reduction of 5.2%, while the then 15 EU member states committed to 8%.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87, which our country will fulfill.
There is a lot going on in Bali, because an international agreement on a long-term climate change policy needs to be adopted within two years, otherwise its entry into force would certainly be postponed until 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new emission reduction system, the need for which is also highlighted in its latest report by the international scientific council of the UN, which is concerned only with climate change.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and inevitably increase the average temperature on Earth by more than 2 degrees Celsius, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
The British army is recruiting on YouTube
British troops are posting videos of events in Iraq and Afghanistan on a video-sharing server, which they use to popularize themselves.
First, YouTube became popular with the British Air Force (RAF): special forces operating in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of anti-Taliban operations since March 2006.
The recordings, taken with a miniature camera attached to the helmet, are inspected by the Air Force Command controlling combat operations in the Kandahar area and then sent to London, where they are transmitted to the Internet.
A political message is unavoidable.
In this form, 139 recordings of British Air Force soldiers have already been made on the Internet, and their "channel" has already been viewed by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 as "defenceheadquarters" and publishes recordings of events in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the British Foreign Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channels.
Deployment in Afghanistan
The Air Force has released videos according to its original intent for recruitment purposes, and according to the Ministry of Defense, they are also good for acquaintance of the general public with the real purpose of the military presence abroad.
“The promotion published in this form costs little compared to traditional television recruitment ads,” said defense expert Gordon Mackenzie, “but it also necessarily carries a certain political message, as it confirms in a special way the legitimacy of the military actions decided by the government.”
The Americans made the game.
The army is concerned that, in addition to carefully edited, censored recordings, amateur videos, for example, depicting the deaths of soldiers, are also being uploaded to the server: in somewhat hypocritical, "official" promotional films, officers talk about losses at the most, but the bloody form of the fight is not shown.
Many videos from the battlefields in Iraq and Afghanistan, which were created during the sharp deployment, have already been made available on the Internet, but the British army has only now discovered them.
Americans recruit a little differently - using a shooting game called America's Army, which is free to download and in which the player can, through a more or less faithful simulation, get directly into the skin of the soldiers.
