It's about to go on a huge strike
The League of Trade Unions, or the National Union of Workers' Councils (MOSZ), will set up its strike committee on Friday to coordinate Monday's unrestricted strike.
A protest public assembly will be held on Saturday, and work will be stopped on Monday - the day of the final vote on the health insurance law.
The action will certainly cause serious traffic interruptions, as rail transport will almost completely stop and the employees of the Budapest Transport Company (BKV) will also strike by 1 p.m.
On Friday afternoon, the League and the National Union of Workers' Councils will present the details of the joint Monday strike.
There will also be a LEAGUE-MOSZ strike committee, which will coordinate Monday's event.
A protest public assembly is held on Saturday, and from Monday, unions joining the strike will suspend work indefinitely unless a deal is reached with the government.
This means that no deadline has been set for the end of the strike, which will begin on the day of the parliamentary vote on the law on health insurance.
If Parliament does not finally pass the health insurance law, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for a strike.
However, if the legislation is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide on the next step.
According to Monday's agenda of Parliament's meeting, it is also possible that the health insurance law will not be voted on until late in the evening or late at night.
Due to the start of the strike on Monday, serious traffic interruptions can be expected: work on the railways will be stopped indefinitely, in the morning part of Budapest's public transport and more than half of Volán's companies may stop.
At the same time, in many places of the country, half the track will also be closed.
Numerous trade unions and civil society organisations have joined the call to strike, the list of which is constantly updated on the League website.
Some organizations announced an indefinite strike, others announced a temporary suspension of work.
By Thursday afternoon, the Hungarian State Railways (M<0xC3><0x81>V) and the Independent Trade Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ) could not even agree on sufficient services, with more and more people travelling by rail at the beginning of the Christmas holidays.
According to the previous announcements, from the start of operation until 13:00, there will be a strike at BKV, from 7 to 9:00 at the Budapest Airport company, a four-hour strike will be organized by the Trade Unions of Workers in the Energy Industry LIGA, the Trade Union of Educators and the Democratic Trade Union of Educators called for a 2-, respectively 2-8-hour stoppage of work.
The Union of Hungarian Physicians will strike alternately across the country, while the Democratic Trade Union of Health and Social Workers (EDDSZ), a member of the Trade Union Cooperation Forum (SZEF), is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands formulated by the League is for the government to withdraw the health insurance reform proposal and submit a new concept for public debate.
The second requirement is that the new method of calculating pensions applicable from next year should be introduced gradually.
Thirdly, to ensure the possibility of early retirement for the relevant occupations before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is that the Independent Trade Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ), which belongs to the League trade union, does not accept the offer of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning railway branches, and expects a different offer.
Political Capital: The Hungarian Guard has increased the risk of the country
The activity of the Hungarian Guard, founded with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért movement in August this year, according to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, has increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
In the "risk warning" prepared by the company, it is written: in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is that "the aggravation of already existing ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Roma populations of Hungary may soon lead to violent ethnic clashes".
The main reason is that the Hungarian Guard’s political strategy is likely to provoke such an action, the research institute adds.
As he writes, all this can be explained by one of the biggest negligences of Hungarian political leaders: "the public discussion of the Roma issue was left to representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who could build a political strategy on the Romani-Hungarian contradiction."
This deepens the problem, prevents normal dialogue, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts.
In addition, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, according to the research institute, under the influence of the great attention of domestic and foreign media, "to a large extent spoiled the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of faith in the stability of the country and its democratic maturity".
The Institute recalls that part of the reorganization of the Hungarian radical and far-right groups, which has been gaining increasing publicity and vehemence since autumn 2006, is that several organizations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007, which themselves call themselves "national militia" associations.
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil associations, while openly proclaiming - even armed - the readiness of their members to perform defensive tasks (in case of natural disasters, invasion of the country, disorder of order), in addition to pointing to the incompetence of the police, the army, or the state," he adds.
All of this is done in a way that seeks to wrap all sorts of political endeavors built on society’s opposition to politics and parties in civilian garb.
Emphasis on civility and the form of the association in the case of these groups serves not only to avoid the legal pitfalls of judicial registration, but is also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk factor in terms of neighbourly relations.
