Holidays are not free everywhere
In Hungary, holidays are precisely defined by law and it has become common practice to move working days around holidays, which is less common next year.
There is no uniform holiday in the European Union or the United States.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between national and national holidays and days of rest.
Days of rest are usually associated with church holidays or important historical events.
In our country, we also celebrate the New Year: the last day of the old and the first day of the new year is a work holiday - on New Year's already so that people can rest after New Year's Eve.
There are eleven free holidays throughout the year.
The national holiday is March 15, celebrating the revolution of 1848, and October 23, the day of the revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August we celebrate the founding of the state, on the 1st of May we celebrate the work, on the 1st and 2nd of November we commemorate the deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, Easter, Pentecost and Christmas are two-day holidays.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on the weekend according to the calendar, it has become a practice to move the working day in cases where we would only work one day before or after a holiday.
However, the price for extended weekends is that we stay in the workplace and at school the previous Saturdays.
The day immediately preceding or following the holiday has been regulated by the Minister of Labour in a special decree for many years.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and workers employed by them, to public servants and to persons in the public service.
However, it does not apply to companies and institutions that are in operation without interruption or, taking into account their destination, operate even on days of rest.
This year, there will be a change in the working conditions only around the holidays at the end of the year: from December 24, life in the country will almost stop, because according to previous experience, most people "work" in advance the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve or thus take advantage of the holidays saved.
Next year, several of our holidays fall in the middle or at the end of the week, so the shifts of the working day will be less than this year.
For the first time, the calendar changes around Labor Day, so that workers can then stay at home for four days of taste.
Saturday, April 26th, will be a working day, so that Friday, May 2nd, can be a day of rest.
The next move is related to the holiday of October 23: Saturday, October 18, will be working instead of Friday, October 24.
By the end of next year, however, it will be possible to take place entirely under the sign of holidays, because from December 24, almost everywhere will have nonstop holidays, even though New Year's Eve falls on Wednesday.
6 Things You Can Do to Annoy Your Colleagues
The emails we forget to send, the voicemails we never receive, the innocent lies we barely notice anymore: all of this “makes” our everyday lives at the workplace more diverse.
The question is whether you get used to these minor inconveniences, or put on gloves and unclear situations that can make others angry, you will deliberately avoid.
Tips.
"I'm sorry, I forgot to tell you that the marketing department was looking for you," a colleague tells you.
That you missed a meeting for that?
In the best case, he regrets it and will try to fix it, or call the marketing department and say that he forgot to pass the message (this is a less common solution).
Most often, the issue is solved with an apology.
Before you make an awkward apology, it’s a good idea to think about what you can do to prepare awkward moments for your colleagues and consciously try to avoid it.
Are you borrowing something that is not yours?
There’s nothing more annoying than when you reach out for a piece of paper, an office item, or your phone, and they’re not there.
Do you remember putting a stapler on your desk yesterday, but it's gone by morning?
Or did you find a pen on the desk of one of your colleagues that you thought was lost?
Do not take anything from your colleagues without permission, otherwise they will be rightfully angry with you for digging into their things.
Do not take envelopes or glue papers out of the office, as they can be annoying if you run out prematurely and you will need them immediately.
Gossip about the private life of colleagues?
There is no good way to stop the spread of rumors.
Who, who, what was he doing?
Where and why?
Don’t tell anyone about your friends’ private lives!
When one of them shares his innermost secrets with you, do not abuse his trust!
Lock in what you have heard, and do not discuss it with your colleagues in his absence, even if others know about his things.
Are you reporting your absence for no reason?
If you call the office and report your absence because you’re not feeling well, or think you’d rather rest today, think that someone else will have to do your job, urgent tasks, and the work that they have a certain deadline for you.
Take care of your colleagues!
If you know in advance that you will not be going to work the next day, or that something may happen that will make you stay home, report it so that your colleagues and managers will not be confronted with your absence until the next day.
Brushing, giggling, phoning
Have you been immersed in a job from which you are rudely pulled out by the giggling of colleagues?
Have you inadvertently witnessed a telephone conversation that would be better not to hear at all?
Do not disturb your co-workers with murmurings, chanting, loud talk (overhead), or treading, constant cursing, loud dissatisfaction.
All this can be disturbing even when they are not prevented from a project (writing, planning, organization).
Do you blame others for the mistakes?
If something is not on time or you forgot to send an important letter or message, do not blame your forgetfulness on others!
Do not appeal to any chaos reigning in the office and noisy colleagues!
Admit if you made a mistake and someone paid for it, and fix the damage!
Ask how you can fix things, correct negligence!
Do you feel too much at home in the office?
Pants and slippers: comfortable clothes for home, but not for the office!
Do not wear casual clothes, even if your profession allows it!
Do not be careless, honor your colleagues and yourself by coming to the office in ordinary clothes - and if your profession requires it, nicely and elegantly!
