A British teacher tried in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced to 15 days in prison by a Khartoum tribunal on Thursday night and expelled, her lawyer said.
A British woman has been accused of allowing six to seven-year-old pupils to give the teddy bear the name Mohammed, despite the fact that any depiction of the prophet of Islam is prohibited.
She was punished with whips.
The 54-year-old British teacher, who works at Unity High School in Sudan’s Khartoum, was arrested at her home on Sunday and charged with insulting Islam and rebellion, in accordance with Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code, after parents of several pupils filed a complaint with the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
In fact, our story begins in September, when the teacher in question asks his six to seven-year-old pupils to choose a name for the class teddy bear.
"Eight names will come out of the children's mouths, including Hasan, Abdullah and Mohammed," said Robert Boulos, the school's director.
After voting in the classroom, 20 of the 23 children will eventually choose Muhammad as their favorite name.
Sure, Muhammad is the name of a Muslim prophet, but above all it is a very common first name in Sudan.
The children then created a book for their class with a picture of a teddy bear accompanied by the caption: "My name is Mohammed".
The bear itself had no label with this name on it, but the difficulty is in depicting the prophet himself, which is considered an insult to Islam.
One fellow Muslim Gillian Gibbons, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, said he knew her well and that she would never do anything that could be offensive to any religious belief: "I only regret that she asked the children to vote for a name," he said it was just an "innocent misconduct."
