But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
For example, is it possible to give them toys?
Of course, it is a matter of interpretation.
In the last round of negotiations this Wednesday in Vienna, they did not reach an agreement on the future status of the province.
Eventually a failure.
Serbs and Kosovo Albanians ended their sixth and final round of talks in Baden, Austria, on Wednesday morning, without overcoming divergent views on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that both sides have not been able to reach an agreement on status," European negotiator Wolfgang Ischinger said at a press conference in Vienna.
His American counterpart, Frank Wisner, stressed that peace in the region is "at stake" and urged Belgrade and Pristina to respect their commitments to peace and be ready for dialogue even after the negotiations have ended.
"We are not expecting violence in the near future, but we are entering a difficult period," he added, adding that "it is obvious that the situation is tense."
Negotiations end on December 10
The negotiators of the Troika, made up of representatives of the European Union, the United States and Russia, will last travel to Kosovo on Monday.
The future of the province, where 90 percent of the population is Albanian-speaking, could be seen in a brighter light by December 10, when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian negotiator Alexander Bocan-Kharchenko are due to submit their report to the UN Security Council.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, mark the sixth and final round of negotiations since the United Nations commissioned the troika to renegotiate in August.
Americans and Europeans expect the talks to end on December 10.
On the other hand, the Russians, who had previously blocked the granting of independence to Kosovo in the UN Security Council, insist that negotiations continue beyond this deadline.
"Russia has been and remains inclined towards a negotiated solution, a compromise solution," Bocan-Kharchenko said.
A unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years of governance by the international community, the West considers Kosovo's EU-supervised independence to be the only viable solution.
Pristina declares that if the Security Council does not decide in its favour, it is ready to declare independence unilaterally.
Belgrade insists on expanded autonomy.
"Unfortunately, we have not reached any agreement," Fatmir Sejdiu, the president of Kosovo's self-government, said in a hotel in Baden, where this "last chance meeting" has been taking place since Monday.
Hashim Thaçi, the former rebel commander of Kosovo Albanians and future prime minister of the province, expressed regret.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade "belongs to a past that has led to murders and deportations".
"The Domino Effect"
Serbian President Boris Tadic, on the other hand, believes that a compromise is still possible and warned the Albanian majority in Kosovo of the consequences of possible unilaterally declared independence of the province.
Belgrade is particularly concerned about the “dominion effect” in an area that is still unstable as a result of the wars of independence in the 1990s.
"But for Serbia, that does not mean," he said, "that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that all decisions should be taken exclusively by the Security Council, in which its Russian ally has veto power.
"Kosovo's parliament will have the final say"
"The only solution acceptable to Serbia is the solution that emerged from the Security Council," Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
"This meeting lasted two years.
It has to end the way it started: in the Security Council."
Fatmir Sedjiu told reporters that "the Kosovo parliament will have the final say on the status" and added that if there was a unilateral declaration of independence by the Albanian-speaking population, it would take place "by agreement" with the West.
