At the opening of an international peace conference in Annapolis, Maryland, convened on his own initiative, US President George Bush announced that Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint statement.
He said Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to immediately start talks to resolve the 60-year-old dispute between the two nations once and for all.
In the presence of both men, Bush promised to do everything possible to help them conclude a “peace treaty” before the end of 2008.
In the meantime, the Palestinians must destroy “terrorist infrastructure” and Israel must put an end to colonial activities, Bush said, recalling the obligations for both sides stemming from the “road map” to peace that they accepted in 2003.
The head of the White House stressed that the negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority, led by Abbas, are aimed at “concluding a peace treaty that would resolve all outstanding issues without exception, including the central issues”.
This statement includes three issues that are at the heart of the dispute between Israelis and Palestinians: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem, and the fate of Arab refugees expelled from their homes in the 1948 conflict in what is now the State of Israel.
Abbas took the floor after the US president, emphasizing that the follow-up talks should be “comprehensive and thorough” and touch upon all aspects of the solution, mentioning “Jerusalem, refugees, borders, colonies, water, security, among other things.”
Olmert then took the floor, expressing the view that the follow-up negotiations should be "direct and continuous" and that "a commitment should be made for them to be concluded during 2008".
Bush set the end of 2008 as the deadline for the realization of his "vision of two states", Palestinian and Israeli, coexisting side by side.
Saudi Arabia said it had taken a commitment from Bush in this regard before deciding to attend the conference.
Saudi Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis is a success for Washington, initiated a proposal adopted by all Arab countries that offers Israel peace in exchange for leaving all Arab territories seized during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
Annapolis stands for “a crossroads in Middle Eastern history, especially because it fights against the roots of the conflict and its central aspects,” Prince Saud said in an interview he gave to an Arabic-speaking newspaper shielded by Saudi capital.
