Preoccupied memory
After more than sixty years in a confidential regime, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which depict the fate of the 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are being opened to the public.
The 47 million archival documents stored over a length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) have so far been accessed only for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is, individually and specifically, at the request of the former victim or his authorized persons.
Eleven states in charge of managing the archives – including Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed in May to open them to scientists and historians.
As the process of ratification of this agreement by all states is over, the opening yesterday came into effect.
Sensitive information
The free access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow to examine "particularly the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of the forced laborers", explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were against making these nominal documents available to the public, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some deportation victims.
The registers of concentration camps or arrest warrants drawn up by the Gestapo after the war were collected for the practical purpose of finding deported or forced labour subjected to civilians, to bring them evidence of their internment in order to open the way for their compensation.
Today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen deal with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen represents only a limited benefit.
"Nothing fundamentally new can be expected from these documents," said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for the Study of Anti-Semitism at Berlin's Technische Universität, in 2006.
