Congress approves MiFID transposition effective November 1
In parallel with the parliamentary negotiations that ended today with a vote by Congress on the amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government has subjected a public hearing to a regulation that is developing the new law, with the aim that both will enter into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the parties agreed on the efforts of MEPs and senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard in order to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of the entities necessary for the effective functioning of the markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, provides for the modernization of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new regulation will allow the provision of financial advisory services to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons, and creates a new type of financial services firms (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFIs) that join securities companies, securities brokerage firms and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the execution of transactions with financial instruments is expanding by joining regulated secondary markets with multilateral trading and order internalisation systems that will compete with current exchange brokers.
The law further obliges firms providing investment services to disseminate on the market information on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and ways of dealing with risk, and requires a record of all operations performed to simplify supervision by the CNMV.
Several adjustments were included in the Congressional Trade Commission's deliberations, among which one stands out to make securitised receivables considered a "complex" financial instrument due to the high risk to the investor that has been demonstrated by what has happened in the US with high-risk mortgage debts (subprime).
Moreover, the transposition of the directive was used to legally define the functions that can be held by bachelors in the field of economics and business management 30 years after the Royal Decree, which sets out professional functions reserved for economists, was approved in 1977.
At the same time, the Senate included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary who will work externally, will not require permission from the CNMV and will be able to provide services of trading in products and acquiring clients for different investment firms at the same time.
