The NHS Chambers are expected to inspect foreign personnel for qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the UK prior to their employment.
Although the Scottish Health Commission uses Disclosure Scotland for criminal records checks, the agency has no authority to obtain such information outside the UK.
The report by the President of the Supreme Audit Office says, among other recommendations, that commissions should be guided by the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with checks in several countries.
"Although we found that some of the personnel records contained evidence of these checks, they are not carried out on a regular basis," the report said.
Mr Black said the Scottish NHS is largely in line with its own pre-employment checks policy, but added: “Our report draws attention to areas where the system could be improved to ensure accurate information about the amount of foreign personnel available.”
