Now there are multifaceted gifts from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour’s secretary general (and their former guardian of internal discipline), has already resigned.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is inevitably heading towards his end.
Nevertheless, governments may reach a tipping point, beyond which they find it difficult to govern.
People don't trust politicians and don't like them, but they usually push their distrust away when a new group takes over.
When it seems clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve anything, and may not even be in office for long, this is a push away: the state administration becomes leaky, ministers begin to make briefings, the press searches for bad news, and the government becomes unfocused and defensive.
In one way, Mr Brown's position is particularly difficult, because he cannot take the position of a new broom compared to other political leaders.
As much as he wanted to distance himself from Tony Blair, he was his first officer.
For example, the problems with Northern Rock and the records of the tax office are related to the decisions Mr Brown made as Secretary of the Treasury.
And even though he was not directly involved in Blair’s troubles, such as the long investigation into the financing of political parties caused by “dignities for money,” voters can safely conclude that he was.
Yet Mr. Brown's troubles are not as bad as they seem.
They’re not as bad as conservatives do.
As far as Mr. Bean is concerned, no one has died or been outright deceived.
And the treatment, however painful it may be, is to provide what Mr. Brown’s Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, firm, and slightly brutal government.
The recent turmoil over political gifts is a good example.
Garboid Mr. Abrahams, who compares his gifts to charity, says he did not wish for any publicity for his charity.
