The laws against the anonymity of large political donors are clear and exist for a simple reason: the public has a right to know who could buy access to those who rule the country.
Mr. Watt, who said he knew of Mr. Abrahams's progress but did not know that he was illegal, would certainly be thoroughly questioned; so would Jon Mendlesohn, the chief Labour money-seeker, who had learned of the fraudulent gifts in October.
But so far Mr. Brown has not been involved in any way; there is nothing to suggest that he was aware of these plots, even though the bulk of the payments took place after his arrival in June.
The Prime Minister has done half the work.
He very quickly condemned this violation of the law by his own party, but diluted his determination by reaching for a proven instrument, a commission to investigate the matter -- led by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the lessons are not complicated.
If the law has been violated, this is a matter for the police.
In addition, there are other things that Mr Brown has to do, such as finding a permanent chairman of the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has had no one for six months, and moving forward with a real reform of the financing of political parties.
This would require Labour, who are in a tight spot, to cooperate with the Conservatives, and perhaps even to give up their special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a devoted party man like Mr Brown.
But he should face a few simple facts.
The Conservatives now have a decent lead in the polls; he has two years to get his voters back; and the only way to win is through undisputed integrity and high competence.
