Is the Mortgage Crisis Affecting the US Credit Card Market?
When there is blood in the water, the dorsal fins naturally begin to stir excitedly around.
With the U.S. real estate market now declining, predators have focused on the credit card market there.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs say credit card losses could reach $99 billion if other variants of consumer credit were infected by subprime mortgages.
The signs of tension are obvious.
There is an increasing number of cases of inability to pay (with more than 30 days of late payment) and write-offs (accounts that the provider considers unenforceable).
Last month, HSBC announced that it had lost $1.4 billion in the U.S. consumer credit market, also due to insolvent credit card loans.
It is too early to panic, however.
The bills written off and the inability to pay are still few.
According to Moody's, the 3.89% insolvency rate in the third quarter was almost a whole percentage point below the average.
The deteriorating rates can partly be explained by technical reasons.
A change in the U.S. Personal Bankruptcy Acts in 2005 led to a sharp decline in the number of reported bankruptcies, which account for a large part of credit card losses; the number of reports (and thus the number of depreciations) would therefore rise regardless of whether the general conditions for borrowers deteriorated.
The industry also has a good maturity rate, which shows how much consumers pay off their debts monthly.
And trust in secured credit card securities is solid, despite paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup predicts that their emissions for 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
Direct pathways to spread infection between the subprime mortgage crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: when property loans run dry, consumers are more likely to get into debt through credit cards.
However, credit card issuers look at cash flow rather than the value of guaranteed items, so falling house prices do not necessarily mean a change in the credibility of borrowers.
They can even be advantageous for loan providers.
Consumers’ motivation to repay mortgages decreases when their assets fall below the value of the loan; as a result, card debt moves up on the repayment priority list.
Card issuers are also able to respond more quickly and flexibly to more turbulent conditions than mortgage providers by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risks of a rapid change in the prices of guarantee items.
“It’s not like we’re going to rethink all of our loans one fine morning,” said Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
Although the risk of an explosion in the style of low-end mortgages is low, the risk of gradual weakening is much more real.
