Venus is the hellish twin of Earth
Despite its life-hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought. The European spacecraft Venus Express on Venus has observed phenomena that occur even on Earth in winter: lightning in the atmosphere and windstorms at the poles.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that Venus is shining.
Now the European probe Venus Express has brought proof - it has captured electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus, lightning flies from cloud to cloud at an altitude of about 56 kilometers, wrote in the scientific magazine Nature Christopher Russell from the University of California, Los Angeles.
According to the known theory of the formation of primordial matter, lightning may have created life on Earth, and storms are said to have triggered reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the foundation stones of life.
This was not the case on Venus: “If life ever existed there, it must have been a long time ago,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institute in Washington.
The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and there are sometimes temperatures around 500 degrees Celsius.
"Venus may be the hellish twin of Earth, but it's a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, began to evolve in a completely different way is a fundamental question of the Asa mission.
Since no spacecraft has been sent to study Venus alone since the early 1990s, the launch of Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in the exploration of the planet.
According to scientists, the latest results of the research, which brought closer several articles in the journal Nature, not only emphasized the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system.
"They also showed that our neighboring planet is more Earth-like than previously thought," said Esa.
In addition to the already known windstorms at the North Pole, scientists have found a cloud vortex at the South Pole that spins considerably faster.
This phenomenon resembles the air currents in the Earth's northern hemisphere, writes the research team led by Guiseppe Piccioni of the Italian Instituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet of our solar system is almost the same mass as Earth and with a diameter of 12,100 km it is almost the same size.
This planet, known as Dawn or Evening, will orbit the Sun in about 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly around its own axis: one day on Venus lasts 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus does not resemble Earth at a surface temperature of 460 °C and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists assume that the two planets were formed under very similar conditions.
Water accumulated on both, but remained in the oceans on Earth, while it evaporated from Venus into space.
While carbon dioxide on Earth is bound in carbonates, it forms most of the atmosphere on Venus.
