These aren't Warhol's boxes.
Anyone who combines the terms Sweden and wooden crates does not think of Andy Warhol, but of Ikea.
Isn't it?
Wooden crates currently manufactured in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol’s list of works.
Most of his listed ninety-four "Brillo boxes" of the Stockholm type are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago, the international market of the "Brillo" of Warhol's "Brillo boxes" of 1968, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm comes with a result that brought disappointment; six "Brillo boxes" of the type "Brillo" of the "Brillo" of the Museum of Moderna Museet are also donated to him.
The preceding events are a tangled, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York in 1964, painting wooden boxes that were based on the red-blue-white design of paper boxes of Brillo soap powder.
The exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 showed - with Warhol's approval - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard. These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
These were not works of art, but their masterpieces, mere exhibits.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 for several wooden Brillo crates to be made in Sweden, but they are not on display at Moderna Museet.
The witnesses now speak of fifteen boxes that rightly entered the art and auction history as authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes" with the designation Type Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned for more than $100,000.
The problem now lies in the fact that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred crates were made and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, 105 Hulten crates were produced in Malmö for the St. Petersburg exhibition only in 1990.
By that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
In addition to the six Brillo boxes owned by the museum, Lars Byström, the top conservator of Moderna Museet, also examined three Brillo boxes from a Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and after their plywood boards were painted with basic paint and oiled with sandpaper.
On the other hand, from the structure of the copies from 1990, it turned out that the paint was applied directly to the plywood board without a previous primer - besides, it is acrylic and not oil paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official list of Brillo boxes," said Moderna Museet's director, Lars Nittve: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to any other conclusions, Moderna Museet will have to classify the material as six boxes of its exhibitions."
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced that it would address the “core allegations” raised about soap powder boxes.
The organization remains in relentless silence.
